Charles Sanders Peirce. Venn was heir to a clerical Evangelical dynasty, but religious doubts led him to resign Holy Orders and instead focus on an academic career. He wrote influential textbooks on probability theory and logic, became a fellow of the Royal Society, and advocated alongside Henry Sidgwick for educational reform, including that of women’s higher education. Moreover, through his students, a direct line can be traced from Venn to the early analytic philosophy of G. E. Moore and Bertrand Russell, and family ties connect him to the famous Bloomsbury group. This essential book takes readers on Venn’s journey from Evangelical son to Cambridge don to explore his life and work in context. Drawing on Venn’s key writings and correspondence, published and unpublished, Lukas M. Verburgt unearths the legacy of the logician’s wide-ranging thinking while offering perspective on broader themes in religion, science, and the university in Victorian Britain. The rich picture that emerges of Venn, the person, is of a man with many sympathies—sometimes mutually reinforcing and at other times outwardly and inwardly contradictory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aLogicianszEnglandvBiography. 0aPhilosopherszEnglandvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aJohn Venn, biography, Victorian Britain, University of Cambridge, history of science, history of philosophy, history of analytic philosophy, Venn diagrams, Clapham Sect.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226815527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226815527/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles